UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# CSS Fundamentals & Selectors — The Complete Guide\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nCSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is the language that transforms raw HTML into visually compelling interfaces. Without CSS, the web would be plain black text on white backgrounds. With CSS mastery, you control every pixel of the user experience.\n\nSelectors are the foundation of CSS — they determine WHICH elements your styles apply to. Writing efficient, correct selectors is the difference between clean, maintainable stylesheets and a specificity nightmare.\n\n> **Industry Reality:** At companies like Flipkart, Swiggy, and HDFC, frontend engineers maintain massive CSS codebases. Poor selector choices lead to specificity wars, unintended overrides, and styles that break when the HTML changes. CSS architecture is a real engineering discipline.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Write any CSS rule correctly with selectors, properties, and values\n- Use all selector types: element, class, ID, attribute, pseudo-class, pseudo-element\n- Understand specificity and the cascade\n- Combine selectors with combinators\n- Use the most efficient selectors for common patterns\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner — CSS Rule Structure\n\n```css\n/* Anatomy of a CSS rule */\nselector {\n  property: value;\n  property: value;\n}\n\n/* Example */\nh1 {\n  color: #1e293b;\n  font-size: 2.25rem;\n  font-weight: 700;\n  line-height: 1.2;\n}\n```\n\n### Intermediate — All Selector Types\n\n```css\n/* === BASIC SELECTORS === */\n\n/* Element (type) selector */\np      { color: #374151; }\nbutton { cursor: pointer; }\n\n/* Class selector — most commonly used */\n.card          { background: white; border-radius: 12px; }\n.card.featured { border: 2px solid gold; }  /* Multiple classes */\n\n/* ID selector — use sparingly (high specificity) */\n#main-nav { position: sticky; top: 0; }\n\n/* Universal selector */\n* { box-sizing: border-box; }\n\n/* Attribute selectors */\na[href]                 { text-decoration: underline; }\na[href^="https"]        { color: green; }  /* starts with */\na[href$=".pdf"]         { color: red; }    /* ends with */\na[href*="rlearn"]       { font-weight: 600; } /* contains */\ninput[type="checkbox"]  { accent-color: #3b82f6; }\ninput[disabled]         { opacity: 0.5; }\n\n/* === COMBINATORS === */\n\n/* Descendant (space) — any level deep */\n.nav a           { color: inherit; }  /* all <a> inside .nav */\n\n/* Child (>) — direct children only */\n.dropdown > li   { display: block; }  /* direct li children */\n\n/* Adjacent sibling (+) — immediately after */\nh2 + p           { font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 500; } /* first p after h2 */\n\n/* General sibling (~) — all after */\n.toggle:checked ~ .panel { display: block; }\n\n/* === PSEUDO-CLASSES === */\n\n/* User action states */\na:hover        { color: #3b82f6; }\nbutton:focus   { outline: 2px solid #3b82f6; outline-offset: 2px; }\ninput:focus-within { border-color: #3b82f6; }\nbutton:active  { transform: scale(0.98); }\n\n/* Structural pseudo-classes */\nli:first-child        { border-top: none; }\nli:last-child         { border-bottom: none; }\nli:nth-child(2n)      { background: #f8fafc; }  /* even items */\nli:nth-child(3n+1)    { color: blue; }           /* 1st, 4th, 7th... */\np:not(.intro)         { margin-bottom: 1rem; }   /* all p except .intro */\n\n/* Form pseudo-classes */\ninput:required        { border-color: #ef4444; }\ninput:valid           { border-color: #10b981; }\ninput:invalid         { border-color: #ef4444; }\ninput:placeholder-shown { opacity: 0.6; }\ninput:checked + label { font-weight: 600; }\n\n/* Link pseudo-classes (order matters: LVHA) */\na:link    { color: #3b82f6; }\na:visited { color: #7c3aed; }\na:hover   { color: #1d4ed8; }\na:active  { color: #1e40af; }\n\n/* === PSEUDO-ELEMENTS === */\n\n/* First letter / line */\np::first-letter { font-size: 2em; float: left; margin-right: 0.1em; }\np::first-line   { font-weight: 500; }\n\n/* Before / after (generated content) */\n.required::after {\n  content: " *";\n  color: #ef4444;\n}\n\n.tooltip::before {\n  content: attr(data-tooltip);  /* Use data attribute */\n  position: absolute;\n  background: #1e293b;\n  color: white;\n  padding: 0.25rem 0.5rem;\n  border-radius: 4px;\n  bottom: 100%;\n  left: 50%;\n  transform: translateX(-50%);\n}\n\n/* Selection highlight */\n::selection {\n  background: #3b82f6;\n  color: white;\n}\n\n/* Placeholder text */\ninput::placeholder {\n  color: #94a3b8;\n  font-style: italic;\n}\n\n/* Scrollbar (Webkit) */\n::-webkit-scrollbar       { width: 8px; }\n::-webkit-scrollbar-track { background: #f1f5f9; }\n::-webkit-scrollbar-thumb { background: #94a3b8; border-radius: 4px; }\n```\n\n### Advanced — Specificity\n\n```\nSpecificity is calculated as (a, b, c) where:\na = number of ID selectors\nb = number of class, attribute, pseudo-class selectors\nc = number of element, pseudo-element selectors\n\n!important       → Overrides all (avoid except for utilities)\nInline style     → (1,0,0,0)\n#id              → (0,1,0,0)\n.class           → (0,0,1,0)\n[attr]           → (0,0,1,0)\n:pseudo-class    → (0,0,1,0)\nelement          → (0,0,0,1)\n::pseudo-element → (0,0,0,1)\n* (universal)    → (0,0,0,0)\n\nExamples:\n#nav a              → (0,1,0,1) = 101\n.card.featured      → (0,0,2,0) = 020\nnav > ul > li > a   → (0,0,0,4) = 004\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\nCSS CASCADE ORDER (later wins, unless specificity differs)\n\nBrowser default styles\n      ↓\nUser stylesheets (accessibility settings)\n      ↓\nAuthor stylesheets (your CSS)\n      ↓\nAuthor !important\n      ↓\nUser !important\n      ↓\nInline styles\n\nWithin same specificity: LAST RULE WINS\n\n\nSELECTOR PERFORMANCE (fastest to slowest)\n\n#id                → Very fast (single lookup)\n.class             → Fast (most common, well-optimized)\nelement            → Fast\n.parent .child     → Slower (reads right to left)\n*                  → Slowest (match everything)\n[attribute]        → Slow (scan all elements)\n\nBest practice: prefer class selectors for styling\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Button Styles with States\n```css\n.btn {\n  display: inline-flex;\n  align-items: center;\n  gap: 0.5rem;\n  padding: 0.625rem 1.25rem;\n  border: none;\n  border-radius: 8px;\n  font-size: 0.875rem;\n  font-weight: 500;\n  cursor: pointer;\n  text-decoration: none;\n  transition: all 150ms ease;\n}\n\n.btn-primary {\n  background: #3b82f6;\n  color: white;\n}\n\n.btn-primary:hover {\n  background: #2563eb;\n  transform: translateY(-1px);\n  box-shadow: 0 4px 12px rgba(59, 130, 246, 0.4);\n}\n\n.btn-primary:active {\n  transform: translateY(0);\n  box-shadow: none;\n}\n\n.btn-primary:focus-visible {\n  outline: 2px solid #3b82f6;\n  outline-offset: 2px;\n}\n\n.btn-primary:disabled {\n  background: #93c5fd;\n  cursor: not-allowed;\n  transform: none;\n}\n\n/* Icon variant */\n.btn-icon {\n  padding: 0.5rem;\n  border-radius: 6px;\n}\n\n/* Size variants */\n.btn-sm { padding: 0.375rem 0.75rem; font-size: 0.75rem; }\n.btn-lg { padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; font-size: 1rem; }\n```\n\n### Example 2 — Card Component\n```css\n.card {\n  background: white;\n  border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;\n  border-radius: 12px;\n  overflow: hidden;\n  transition: box-shadow 200ms ease, transform 200ms ease;\n}\n\n.card:hover {\n  box-shadow: 0 10px 40px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);\n  transform: translateY(-2px);\n}\n\n.card-image {\n  width: 100%;\n  aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;\n  object-fit: cover;\n  display: block;\n}\n\n.card-body { padding: 1.5rem; }\n\n.card-badge {\n  display: inline-block;\n  padding: 0.25rem 0.75rem;\n  border-radius: 9999px;\n  font-size: 0.75rem;\n  font-weight: 500;\n  background: #eff6ff;\n  color: #1d4ed8;\n  margin-bottom: 0.75rem;\n}\n\n.card-title {\n  font-size: 1.125rem;\n  font-weight: 600;\n  color: #0f172a;\n  margin-bottom: 0.5rem;\n  line-height: 1.4;\n\n  /* Truncate to 2 lines */\n  display: -webkit-box;\n  -webkit-line-clamp: 2;\n  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;\n  overflow: hidden;\n}\n\n.card:focus-within { box-shadow: 0 0 0 2px #3b82f6; }\n.card-title a:focus { outline: none; }  /* outline on card instead */\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Form Styling\n```css\n.field {\n  display: flex;\n  flex-direction: column;\n  gap: 0.375rem;\n  margin-bottom: 1.25rem;\n}\n\n.field label {\n  font-size: 0.875rem;\n  font-weight: 500;\n  color: #374151;\n}\n\n.field input,\n.field select,\n.field textarea {\n  width: 100%;\n  padding: 0.625rem 0.875rem;\n  border: 1px solid #d1d5db;\n  border-radius: 8px;\n  font-size: 0.875rem;\n  color: #111827;\n  background: white;\n  transition: border-color 150ms, box-shadow 150ms;\n}\n\n.field input:focus,\n.field select:focus,\n.field textarea:focus {\n  outline: none;\n  border-color: #3b82f6;\n  box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px rgba(59, 130, 246, 0.15);\n}\n\n.field input:invalid:not(:placeholder-shown) {\n  border-color: #ef4444;\n}\n\n.field .error {\n  font-size: 0.75rem;\n  color: #ef4444;\n  display: flex;\n  align-items: center;\n  gap: 0.25rem;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise 1 — Specificity Calculator\nPredict which style wins and explain why:\n```css\n/* Rule 1 */ #header .nav a { color: red; }\n/* Rule 2 */ .nav a:hover   { color: blue; }\n/* Rule 3 */ nav > ul > li > a { color: green; }\n```\n\n### Exercise 2 — Zebra Table\nStyle a table with alternating row colors using only `:nth-child()`.\n\n### Exercise 3 — Pure CSS Tooltip\nUsing `::before` and `:hover`, create a tooltip that appears above any element with a `data-tooltip` attribute.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Common Mistakes\n\n| Mistake | Problem | Fix |\n|---------|---------|-----|\n| ID selectors everywhere | High specificity, hard to override | Use classes instead |\n| `!important` overuse | Specificity arms race | Fix specificity properly |\n| Too-specific selectors | Break when HTML changes | `.card-title` not `div > article > h3` |\n| :hover without :focus | Keyboard inaccessible | Always pair `:hover` with `:focus-visible` |\n| Descendant over child | Unintended matches | Use `>` when only direct children |\n\n---\n\n## 8. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: How does CSS specificity work?**\n> Specificity is calculated as (ID count, class/attr/pseudo-class count, element/pseudo-element count). Higher specificity wins regardless of source order. When equal specificity, last declaration wins. `!important` overrides all (avoid it).\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `::before` and `:before`?**\n> Single colon `:before` is CSS2 syntax (still works for backward compatibility). Double colon `::before` is CSS3 syntax, preferred for pseudo-elements. Pseudo-classes (`:hover`, `:focus`) always use single colon. Use `::` for pseudo-elements, `:` for pseudo-classes.\n\n**Q: What does the cascade in CSS mean?**\n> Cascade means rules from multiple sources combine and override each other in a defined order: browser defaults → user styles → author styles → inline styles → !important declarations. Within the same source, specificity determines which rule wins, with source order as a tiebreaker.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is the specificity of `.nav > li > a`?\n2. What does `*` select?\n3. What is the difference between `:hover` and `:focus`?\n4. How do you select every third list item?\n5. What combinator selects only direct children?\n6. What does `a[href^="https"]` select?\n7. What is the difference between `::before` and `::after`?\n8. What does `:not()` do?\n9. In what order should link pseudo-classes be defined?\n10. Why should you avoid ID selectors for styling?\n\n---\n\n## 10. Lesson Summary\n\n| Selector Type | Syntax | Specificity |\n|--------------|--------|-------------|\n| Element | `p` | 0,0,1 |\n| Class | `.card` | 0,1,0 |\n| ID | `#header` | 1,0,0 |\n| Attribute | `[type]` | 0,1,0 |\n| Pseudo-class | `:hover` | 0,1,0 |\n| Pseudo-element | `::before` | 0,0,1 |\n| Descendant | `.nav a` | Combined |\n| Child | `.nav > a` | Combined |\n\nCSS selectors are your targeting system. Write them with precision — too broad and you style things unintentionally, too specific and they break when HTML changes. The class selector is almost always the right choice.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l20101';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Colors, Typography & Units — Designing with Precision\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nColor and typography are the most powerful visual tools in your CSS toolkit. Get them right and your UI looks professional and trustworthy. Get them wrong and it looks cheap, regardless of the layout.\n\nUnits determine HOW sizes are calculated — pixels, percentages, em, rem, viewport units. Choosing the wrong unit is one of the most common reasons CSS breaks on different screen sizes.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Use all CSS color formats (hex, rgb, hsl, oklch)\n- Build a complete color system with CSS custom properties\n- Set up a professional typography system\n- Know every CSS unit and when to use each\n- Use `clamp()` for fluid responsive typography\n\n---\n\n## 3. Core Concepts\n\n### CSS Color Formats\n\n```css\n/* Hex — most common, 3 or 6 digits */\ncolor: #3b82f6;       /* Blue */\ncolor: #3b82f680;     /* Blue with 50% opacity (8-digit hex) */\ncolor: #38f;          /* Shorthand: same as #3388ff */\n\n/* RGB / RGBA */\ncolor: rgb(59, 130, 246);          /* Same blue */\ncolor: rgb(59 130 246);            /* Modern space syntax */\ncolor: rgb(59 130 246 / 0.5);      /* With opacity */\ncolor: rgba(59, 130, 246, 0.5);    /* Old opacity syntax */\n\n/* HSL — most intuitive for adjusting colors */\ncolor: hsl(217, 91%, 60%);         /* hue, saturation, lightness */\ncolor: hsl(217deg 91% 60%);        /* Modern syntax */\ncolor: hsl(217 91% 60% / 0.5);     /* With opacity */\n\n/* OKLCH — modern, perceptually uniform (2023+) */\ncolor: oklch(0.65 0.18 260);       /* lightness chroma hue */\n\n/* Named colors */\ncolor: transparent;\ncolor: currentColor;               /* Inherits color property */\ncolor: inherit;\n```\n\n### Typography System\n\n```css\n/* Import Google Fonts */\n@import url(''https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@400;500;600;700&display=swap'');\n\n:root {\n  /* Font families */\n  --font-sans:  ''Inter'', system-ui, -apple-system, sans-serif;\n  --font-mono:  ''Fira Code'', ''Cascadia Code'', monospace;\n\n  /* Font scale (1.25 ratio = Major Third) */\n  --text-xs:   0.75rem;    /* 12px */\n  --text-sm:   0.875rem;   /* 14px */\n  --text-base: 1rem;       /* 16px */\n  --text-lg:   1.125rem;   /* 18px */\n  --text-xl:   1.25rem;    /* 20px */\n  --text-2xl:  1.5rem;     /* 24px */\n  --text-3xl:  1.875rem;   /* 30px */\n  --text-4xl:  2.25rem;    /* 36px */\n\n  /* Line heights */\n  --leading-tight:  1.25;\n  --leading-normal: 1.5;\n  --leading-relaxed: 1.75;\n\n  /* Font weights */\n  --weight-normal:  400;\n  --weight-medium:  500;\n  --weight-semibold: 600;\n  --weight-bold:    700;\n\n  /* Letter spacing */\n  --tracking-tight: -0.025em;\n  --tracking-normal: 0;\n  --tracking-wide:  0.025em;\n  --tracking-wider: 0.05em;\n  --tracking-widest: 0.1em;\n}\n\n/* Typography reset */\nbody {\n  font-family: var(--font-sans);\n  font-size: var(--text-base);\n  line-height: var(--leading-normal);\n  color: #0f172a;\n  -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;\n}\n\n/* Heading styles */\nh1 { font-size: var(--text-4xl); font-weight: var(--weight-bold); line-height: var(--leading-tight); letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight); }\nh2 { font-size: var(--text-3xl); font-weight: var(--weight-semibold); line-height: var(--leading-tight); }\nh3 { font-size: var(--text-2xl); font-weight: var(--weight-semibold); }\n```\n\n### CSS Units — Complete Reference\n\n```css\n/* === ABSOLUTE UNITS === */\npx  /* Pixels — absolute, ignore user font size setting */\npt  /* Points (1pt = 1.33px) — print-only */\ncm, mm, in  /* Physical — print-only */\n\n/* === RELATIVE TO FONT SIZE === */\nem  /* Relative to PARENT font size (compounds!) */\nrem /* Relative to ROOT font size (html element) — prefer this */\n\n/* em example (compounds) */\n.parent { font-size: 20px; }\n.child  { font-size: 1.5em; }   /* 30px */\n.grandchild { font-size: 1.5em; } /* 45px! — compounds! */\n\n/* rem example (predictable) */\nhtml  { font-size: 16px; }       /* Root */\n.any  { font-size: 1.5rem; }     /* Always 24px */\n\n/* === RELATIVE TO VIEWPORT === */\nvw  /* 1% of viewport WIDTH */\nvh  /* 1% of viewport HEIGHT */\nvmin /* 1% of smaller dimension */\nvmax /* 1% of larger dimension */\ndvh /* Dynamic viewport height (mobile-aware) */\n\n/* === RELATIVE TO CONTAINER (Container Queries) === */\ncqw, cqh  /* Container query width/height */\n\n/* === FRACTIONAL (Grid/Flex) === */\nfr  /* Fraction of available space in grid */\n\n/* === PERCENTAGE === */\n%   /* Relative to parent''s same property */\n\n/* === WHEN TO USE WHICH === */\n/* px  → Borders (1px border), shadows, icons */\n/* rem → Font sizes, spacing (consistent with user prefs) */\n/* em  → Component-internal spacing (scales with font) */\n/* %   → Widths, heights relative to parent */\n/* vw/vh → Full-screen sections, hero heights */\n/* fr  → Grid track sizing */\n```\n\n### Fluid Typography with clamp()\n\n```css\n/* clamp(minimum, preferred, maximum) */\n/* preferred is usually viewport-relative */\n\nh1 {\n  /* Min: 24px, Max: 48px, scales between based on viewport */\n  font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 4vw, 3rem);\n}\n\np {\n  font-size: clamp(0.875rem, 2vw, 1.125rem);\n  line-height: 1.6;\n}\n\n.hero {\n  padding: clamp(2rem, 8vh, 6rem);\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Color System Example\n\n```css\n:root {\n  /* Brand colors */\n  --color-primary-50:  #eff6ff;\n  --color-primary-100: #dbeafe;\n  --color-primary-200: #bfdbfe;\n  --color-primary-500: #3b82f6;\n  --color-primary-600: #2563eb;\n  --color-primary-700: #1d4ed8;\n  --color-primary-900: #1e3a8a;\n\n  /* Neutral (gray) scale */\n  --color-gray-50:  #f8fafc;\n  --color-gray-100: #f1f5f9;\n  --color-gray-200: #e2e8f0;\n  --color-gray-300: #cbd5e1;\n  --color-gray-400: #94a3b8;\n  --color-gray-500: #64748b;\n  --color-gray-600: #475569;\n  --color-gray-700: #334155;\n  --color-gray-800: #1e293b;\n  --color-gray-900: #0f172a;\n\n  /* Semantic colors */\n  --color-success: #10b981;\n  --color-warning: #f59e0b;\n  --color-error:   #ef4444;\n  --color-info:    #06b6d4;\n\n  /* Semantic text */\n  --text-primary:   var(--color-gray-900);\n  --text-secondary: var(--color-gray-600);\n  --text-disabled:  var(--color-gray-400);\n\n  /* Semantic backgrounds */\n  --bg-page:    var(--color-gray-50);\n  --bg-surface: white;\n  --bg-subtle:  var(--color-gray-100);\n}\n\n/* Dark mode overrides */\n@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {\n  :root {\n    --text-primary:   var(--color-gray-100);\n    --text-secondary: var(--color-gray-400);\n    --bg-page:    var(--color-gray-900);\n    --bg-surface: var(--color-gray-800);\n    --bg-subtle:  var(--color-gray-700);\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `em` and `rem`?**\n> `em` is relative to the font-size of its PARENT element. It compounds — if parent is 20px and child uses 1.5em, child is 30px. `rem` is relative to the ROOT element (html) — typically 16px. It never compounds. Use `rem` for font sizes and spacing for predictability.\n\n**Q: When would you use HSL over hex color values?**\n> HSL is better when you need to create color variations: lightening, darkening, or adjusting saturation. For example, `hsl(217, 91%, 60%)` → make darker: `hsl(217, 91%, 40%)`, lighter: `hsl(217, 91%, 80%)`. With hex you would need a color picker. HSL also makes it easy to create harmonious color palettes.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What CSS unit is relative to the root font size?\n2. How do you add 50% opacity using hex color notation?\n3. What is the difference between `em` and `rem`?\n4. What are the three values in HSL notation?\n5. What does `currentColor` refer to?\n6. What is `clamp()` used for?\n7. What unit represents 1% of the viewport width?\n8. When should you use `dvh` instead of `vh`?\n9. What font-size percentage equivalent is `1rem` when html has `font-size: 62.5%`?\n10. What is the recommended approach for building a color system?\n\n---\n\n## 7. Lesson Summary\n\n| Unit | Relative To | Use For |\n|------|-------------|----------|\n| `px` | Absolute | Borders, shadows |\n| `rem` | Root font size | All typography and spacing |\n| `em` | Parent font size | Component-internal sizing |\n| `%` | Parent dimension | Widths, responsive sizing |\n| `vw/vh` | Viewport | Full-screen sections |\n| `fr` | Grid container | Grid track sizing |\n| `clamp()` | Multiple | Fluid responsive values |\n\nColor and typography are your primary design tools. Build systems (color scale + type scale) rather than one-off values, and your UI will feel cohesive, professional, and maintainable.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l20201';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# The Box Model & Spacing — Mastering CSS Layout Foundation\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nEvery single HTML element is a rectangular box. The CSS box model defines how that box is sized, padded, bordered, and margined. Understanding the box model is the single most important CSS concept — it explains why elements are the size they are and why your layouts sometimes overflow or collapse.\n\n> **Reality Check:** Box model confusion is the #1 CSS bug source for beginners. "Why is this div wider than its container?" Almost always: box model. "Why does margin collapse?" Box model. Master it once and a huge category of CSS bugs disappears.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Understand the four layers of the box model: content, padding, border, margin\n- Know the difference between `box-sizing: content-box` and `border-box`\n- Use shorthand padding and margin notation fluently\n- Understand margin collapse and when it happens\n- Use `outline` vs `border` correctly\n- Control overflow behavior\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### The Four Layers\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                    MARGIN                           │\n│  ┌───────────────────────────────────────────────┐  │\n│  │                  BORDER                       │  │\n│  │  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐  │  │\n│  │  │               PADDING                   │  │  │\n│  │  │  ┌───────────────────────────────────┐  │  │  │\n│  │  │  │           CONTENT                 │  │  │  │\n│  │  │  │   (width × height)                │  │  │  │\n│  │  │  └───────────────────────────────────┘  │  │  │\n│  │  └─────────────────────────────────────────┘  │  │\n│  └───────────────────────────────────────────────┘  │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### box-sizing — The Critical Setting\n\n```css\n/* content-box (DEFAULT — confusing) */\n.box {\n  box-sizing: content-box; /* default */\n  width: 200px;\n  padding: 20px;\n  border: 2px solid black;\n  /* Actual rendered width: 200 + 20+20 + 2+2 = 244px! */\n}\n\n/* border-box (MODERN — use this always) */\n.box {\n  box-sizing: border-box;\n  width: 200px;\n  padding: 20px;\n  border: 2px solid black;\n  /* Actual rendered width: 200px — always what you set */\n  /* Content width: 200 - 20 - 20 - 2 - 2 = 156px (auto-calculated) */\n}\n\n/* Apply globally — do this in every project */\n*, *::before, *::after {\n  box-sizing: border-box;\n}\n```\n\n### Padding & Margin Shorthand\n\n```css\n/* One value — all sides */\npadding: 1rem;\n\n/* Two values — vertical | horizontal */\npadding: 1rem 2rem;\n/* top&bottom=1rem, left&right=2rem */\n\n/* Three values — top | horizontal | bottom */\npadding: 1rem 2rem 0.5rem;\n\n/* Four values — top | right | bottom | left (clockwise!) */\npadding: 1rem 2rem 0.5rem 1.5rem;\n\n/* Individual sides */\npadding-top:    1rem;\npadding-right:  2rem;\npadding-bottom: 0.5rem;\npadding-left:   1.5rem;\n\n/* Logical properties (RTL-aware) */\npadding-block:        1rem;     /* top + bottom */\npadding-inline:       2rem;     /* left + right */\npadding-block-start:  1rem;     /* top (or right in RTL) */\npadding-inline-end:   2rem;     /* right (or left in RTL) */\n```\n\n### Margin Collapse\n\n```css\n/* Two adjacent vertical margins COLLAPSE to the larger one */\n\n.box-a { margin-bottom: 2rem; }\n.box-b { margin-top: 1rem; }\n/* Actual gap between them: 2rem (NOT 3rem) */\n\n/* Margin collapse happens: */\n/* 1. Between adjacent block elements (vertical only) */\n/* 2. Parent''s margin-top with first child''s margin-top */\n/* 3. Empty blocks with their own top/bottom margin */\n\n/* Margin collapse DOES NOT happen: */\n/* - Horizontal margins */\n/* - Flex/grid children */\n/* - Elements with padding/border between them */\n/* - When overflow is not visible on parent */\n\n/* FIX for parent-child collapse: */\n.parent {\n  padding-top: 1px;          /* Adds barrier */\n  /* OR */\n  border-top: 1px solid transparent;\n  /* OR */\n  overflow: hidden;\n  /* OR */\n  display: flex;\n}\n```\n\n### Width and Height\n\n```css\n.element {\n  /* Fixed sizes */\n  width: 300px;\n  height: 200px;\n\n  /* Constrained sizes */\n  min-width: 200px;\n  max-width: 800px;\n  min-height: 100px;\n  max-height: 400px;\n\n  /* Percentage */\n  width: 50%;   /* 50% of parent''s width */\n  height: 50%;  /* 50% of parent''s HEIGHT (only if parent has height!) */\n\n  /* Viewport */\n  width: 100vw;\n  height: 100vh;\n\n  /* Content-based */\n  width: fit-content;   /* Shrink to content, max at parent width */\n  width: min-content;   /* Minimum possible width */\n  width: max-content;   /* Maximum — no wrapping */\n\n  /* Auto */\n  width: auto;  /* For block: fills container; for inline: shrinks to content */\n}\n\n/* Aspect ratio */\n.video-container {\n  width: 100%;\n  aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;  /* Always 16:9 regardless of width */\n}\n\n.avatar {\n  width: 48px;\n  aspect-ratio: 1;        /* Square */\n  border-radius: 50%;     /* Circle */\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Card with Perfect Spacing\n```css\n.card {\n  box-sizing: border-box;      /* Always */\n  width: 320px;\n  padding: 1.5rem;             /* Internal spacing */\n  border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;\n  border-radius: 12px;\n  margin: 1rem;                /* External spacing */\n\n  /* Overflow for long content */\n  overflow: hidden;\n}\n\n.card-image {\n  /* Negative margin to break out of padding */\n  margin: -1.5rem -1.5rem 1.5rem -1.5rem;\n  width: calc(100% + 3rem);\n  aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;\n  object-fit: cover;\n}\n```\n\n### Example 2 — Auto-centering with Margin\n```css\n/* Centering a block element horizontally */\n.container {\n  max-width: 1200px;\n  margin-left: auto;\n  margin-right: auto;\n  padding-inline: 1.5rem;  /* Side gutters */\n}\n\n/* Shorthand */\n.container {\n  max-width: 1200px;\n  margin: 0 auto;     /* 0 top/bottom, auto left/right */\n  padding: 0 1.5rem;\n}\n\n/* Modern approach */\n.container {\n  max-width: 1200px;\n  margin-inline: auto;     /* Logical property */\n  padding-inline: 1.5rem;\n}\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Overflow Control\n```css\n/* Text truncation with ellipsis */\n.truncate {\n  white-space: nowrap;\n  overflow: hidden;\n  text-overflow: ellipsis;\n  max-width: 200px;\n}\n\n/* Multi-line truncation (2 lines) */\n.clamp-2 {\n  display: -webkit-box;\n  -webkit-line-clamp: 2;\n  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;\n  overflow: hidden;\n}\n\n/* Scroll within container */\n.scrollable {\n  max-height: 400px;\n  overflow-y: auto;\n  overflow-x: hidden;\n  /* Fancy scrollbar */\n  scrollbar-width: thin;\n  scrollbar-color: #94a3b8 transparent;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `border-box` and `content-box`?**\n> With `content-box` (default), width/height apply to the content area only — padding and border are ADDED to the total. With `border-box`, width/height include content + padding + border — it''s the actual rendered size. `border-box` is far more intuitive and predictable. Always set it globally with `*, *::before, *::after { box-sizing: border-box; }`.\n\n**Q: When does margin collapse occur and how do you prevent it?**\n> Margin collapse occurs between adjacent block elements'' vertical margins (takes the larger value), and between a parent and its first/last child. It does NOT occur in flex/grid children, horizontally, or when there''s padding/border between the elements. Prevent with: `overflow: hidden`, `padding-top: 1px`, or `display: flex/grid` on parent.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What are the four layers of the CSS box model?\n2. What does `box-sizing: border-box` change?\n3. What does `padding: 1rem 2rem` mean?\n4. What is margin collapse?\n5. What is `margin: 0 auto` used for?\n6. What is the difference between `outline` and `border`?\n7. How do you truncate text with an ellipsis?\n8. What does `width: fit-content` do?\n9. How do you create a perfectly square element using CSS?\n10. When does margin collapse NOT happen?\n\n---\n\n## 7. Lesson Summary\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---------|---------|\n| `box-sizing: border-box` | Width includes padding+border |\n| `padding` | Space inside the border |\n| `margin` | Space outside the border |\n| `margin: 0 auto` | Horizontal centering |\n| `max-width` | Prevent overly wide containers |\n| `overflow: hidden` | Clip content to box |\n| `aspect-ratio` | Maintain proportions |\n\nThe box model is the physics engine of CSS layout. Once you understand it deeply — especially border-box — positioning and sizing challenges become predictable and solvable.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l20301';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# CSS Positioning & Display — Taking Control of Layout\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nPositioning and display modes are how CSS controls WHERE elements appear on the page. Most layout bugs come from misunderstanding how `position`, `display`, `z-index`, and stacking contexts interact.\n\nMastering these means you can build any layout: sticky headers, fixed sidebars, overlapping elements, dropdown menus, modal overlays, tooltips — anything.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Understand the five `position` values and when to use each\n- Know all `display` values and what they change\n- Control stacking order with `z-index` and stacking contexts\n- Build common UI patterns using positioning\n- Use `transform`, `overflow`, and `clip-path` for visual effects\n\n---\n\n## 3. Display Values\n\n```css\n/* BLOCK — Takes full width, stacks vertically */\ndiv, p, h1, section, article { display: block; }\n.block { display: block; }\n\n/* INLINE — Only as wide as content, flows with text, NO width/height */\nspan, a, strong, em { display: inline; }\n.inline { display: inline; }\n\n/* INLINE-BLOCK — Inline flow BUT accepts width/height */\n.badge { display: inline-block; padding: 0.25rem 0.75rem; }\n\n/* NONE — Removes from layout AND accessibility tree */\n.hidden { display: none; }\n\n/* FLEX — Flexible box layout (1D) */\n.nav { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1rem; }\n\n/* GRID — Grid layout (2D) */\n.layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr; }\n\n/* CONTENTS — Element disappears but children remain */\n/* Useful for custom list markup with flex/grid */\n.wrapper { display: contents; }\n\n/* TABLE family — For complex data only, not layout */\ntable { display: table; }\nth, td { display: table-cell; }\ntr { display: table-row; }\n```\n\n### Position Values\n\n```css\n/* STATIC (default) — normal document flow, top/left/etc ignored */\n.normal { position: static; }\n\n/* RELATIVE — offset from where it WOULD be, space still reserved */\n.offset {\n  position: relative;\n  top: 10px;    /* Move DOWN 10px from normal position */\n  left: 20px;   /* Move RIGHT 20px */\n  /* Other elements act as if this is still in original position */\n}\n\n/* ABSOLUTE — removed from flow, positioned relative to nearest positioned ancestor */\n.tooltip {\n  position: absolute;\n  top: 100%;       /* Below the parent */\n  left: 50%;\n  transform: translateX(-50%);\n  /* If no positioned ancestor, positions relative to initial containing block */\n}\n\n/* Need a positioned parent for absolute children! */\n.parent {\n  position: relative; /* Creates containing block */\n}\n\n/* FIXED — removed from flow, positioned relative to VIEWPORT */\n.topbar {\n  position: fixed;\n  top: 0;\n  left: 0;\n  right: 0;       /* Stretch full width */\n  z-index: 100;\n  /* Stays in place during scroll */\n}\n\n/* STICKY — hybrid: relative until threshold, then fixed */\n.section-header {\n  position: sticky;\n  top: 64px;        /* Sticks when 64px from top of viewport */\n  background: white;\n  z-index: 10;\n  /* Goes back to relative when section scrolls off screen */\n}\n```\n\n### z-index and Stacking Contexts\n\n```css\n/* z-index only works on POSITIONED elements (not static) */\n.modal-overlay {\n  position: fixed;\n  z-index: 1000;\n}\n\n.modal {\n  position: relative;  /* or fixed, absolute */\n  z-index: 1001;\n}\n\n.tooltip {\n  position: absolute;\n  z-index: 100;\n}\n\n/* STACKING CONTEXT — a new "layer" that contains z-index children */\n/* A new stacking context is created by: */\n.creates-stacking-context {\n  opacity: 0.99;        /* Any opacity < 1 */\n  transform: scale(1);  /* Any transform */\n  will-change: transform;\n  isolation: isolate;   /* Explicitly create stacking context */\n  z-index: 0;           /* On positioned element */\n}\n\n/* z-index Z-INDEX SYSTEM */\n:root {\n  --z-dropdown: 100;\n  --z-sticky:   200;\n  --z-modal:    300;\n  --z-toast:    400;\n  --z-tooltip:  500;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Common Positioning Patterns\n\n### Pattern 1 — Overlay Badge\n```css\n.card {\n  position: relative; /* Containing block */\n}\n\n.badge {\n  position: absolute;\n  top: 0.75rem;\n  right: 0.75rem;\n  background: #ef4444;\n  color: white;\n  font-size: 0.75rem;\n  padding: 0.25rem 0.5rem;\n  border-radius: 9999px;\n}\n```\n\n### Pattern 2 — Sticky Table Headers\n```css\ntable { border-collapse: collapse; }\n\nthead th {\n  position: sticky;\n  top: 0;\n  background: white;\n  z-index: 1;\n  border-bottom: 2px solid #e2e8f0;\n}\n```\n\n### Pattern 3 — Modal/Dialog Overlay\n```css\n.modal-overlay {\n  position: fixed;\n  inset: 0;           /* top:0 right:0 bottom:0 left:0 */\n  background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);\n  display: flex;\n  align-items: center;\n  justify-content: center;\n  z-index: 1000;\n}\n\n.modal {\n  position: relative;\n  background: white;\n  border-radius: 16px;\n  padding: 2rem;\n  max-width: 480px;\n  width: 90%;\n  max-height: 90vh;\n  overflow-y: auto;\n  z-index: 1001;\n}\n```\n\n### Pattern 4 — Tooltip\n```css\n.tooltip-wrapper {\n  position: relative;\n  display: inline-flex;\n}\n\n.tooltip {\n  position: absolute;\n  bottom: calc(100% + 8px);\n  left: 50%;\n  transform: translateX(-50%);\n  background: #1e293b;\n  color: white;\n  font-size: 0.75rem;\n  padding: 0.375rem 0.75rem;\n  border-radius: 6px;\n  white-space: nowrap;\n  pointer-events: none;\n\n  /* Arrow */\n  &::after {\n    content: "";\n    position: absolute;\n    top: 100%;\n    left: 50%;\n    transform: translateX(-50%);\n    border: 5px solid transparent;\n    border-top-color: #1e293b;\n  }\n}\n\n.tooltip-wrapper:hover .tooltip,\n.tooltip-wrapper:focus-within .tooltip {\n  opacity: 1;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `position: absolute` and `position: fixed`?**\n> `absolute` positions the element relative to its nearest positioned ancestor (or the initial containing block if none). It scrolls with the page. `fixed` positions relative to the viewport and stays in place while scrolling. Both remove the element from normal document flow.\n\n**Q: What is a stacking context and why does it matter?**\n> A stacking context is a three-dimensional conceptual layer that contains elements with z-index values. z-index values only compare within the same stacking context. A child element with z-index:9999 cannot appear above a sibling stacking context with z-index:1. Created by: opacity < 1, transform, filter, isolation:isolate. This explains why a high z-index "doesn''t work" — it''s in a different stacking context.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does `position: relative` do when no offsets are set?\n2. What does `inset: 0` set?\n3. What is required for `z-index` to have any effect?\n4. How does `position: sticky` differ from `position: fixed`?\n5. What element does `position: absolute` position relative to?\n6. What is the difference between `display: none` and `visibility: hidden`?\n7. How do you create a full-screen overlay with CSS?\n8. What creates a stacking context?\n9. What does `isolation: isolate` do?\n10. How do you center an absolutely-positioned element?\n\n---\n\n## 7. Lesson Summary\n\n| Position | In Flow | Positioned Relative To |\n|----------|---------|------------------------|\n| `static` | ✅ | N/A (default) |\n| `relative` | ✅ | Own original position |\n| `absolute` | ❌ | Nearest positioned ancestor |\n| `fixed` | ❌ | Viewport |\n| `sticky` | ✅/❌ | Scroll container + threshold |\n\nPositioning and display modes unlock every advanced layout pattern. Master these and you can build any interface — modals, tooltips, sticky headers, overlays — with clean, understandable CSS.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l20401';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# CSS Grid Layout — Two-Dimensional Mastery\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nCSS Grid is the most powerful layout system in CSS history. Unlike Flexbox (one-dimensional), Grid controls BOTH rows AND columns simultaneously. Complex page layouts that once required JavaScript frameworks can now be built in 5 lines of CSS.\n\n> **Industry Reality:** Every modern dashboard, e-commerce product grid, blog layout, and admin panel uses CSS Grid. Figma designs hand-crafted by designers? CSS Grid makes them buildable with pixel-perfect precision.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Define grid templates with rows, columns, and named areas\n- Place items using line numbers, named lines, and area names\n- Use `auto-fill`, `auto-fit`, and `minmax()` for responsive grids\n- Understand implicit vs explicit grid\n- Build common layout patterns: dashboard, magazine, masonry\n\n---\n\n## 3. Core Concepts\n\n```css\n/* Enable Grid */\n.container {\n  display: grid;\n\n  /* Define columns */\n  grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr 1fr;    /* 3 columns: fixed | flexible | flexible */\n  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);   /* 3 equal columns */\n  grid-template-columns: repeat(12, 1fr);  /* 12-column grid */\n  grid-template-columns: 240px 1fr;        /* sidebar + main */\n\n  /* Define rows */\n  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;       /* header + content + footer */\n  grid-template-rows: 64px 1fr 80px;\n\n  /* Gap between cells */\n  gap: 1.5rem;              /* Both axes */\n  row-gap: 1rem;            /* Rows only */\n  column-gap: 1.5rem;       /* Columns only */\n}\n\n/* Item placement */\n.item {\n  /* Span across columns */\n  grid-column: 1 / 3;       /* From line 1 to line 3 (spans 2) */\n  grid-column: 1 / -1;      /* From first to LAST line (full width) */\n  grid-column: span 2;      /* Span 2 columns from current position */\n\n  /* Span across rows */\n  grid-row: 1 / 3;          /* 2 rows tall */\n  grid-row: span 2;\n}\n\n/* Shorthand */\n.item { grid-area: 1 / 1 / 3 / 3; }  /* row-start / col-start / row-end / col-end */\n```\n\n### Named Grid Areas — Most Readable Approach\n\n```css\n.app {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-columns: 240px 1fr;\n  grid-template-rows: 64px 1fr 60px;\n  grid-template-areas:\n    "sidebar header"\n    "sidebar main  "\n    "sidebar footer";\n  min-height: 100vh;\n}\n\n.header  { grid-area: header; }\n.sidebar { grid-area: sidebar; }\n.main    { grid-area: main; }\n.footer  { grid-area: footer; }\n\n/* Responsive — collapse on mobile */\n@media (max-width: 768px) {\n  .app {\n    grid-template-columns: 1fr;\n    grid-template-rows: 64px auto 1fr 60px;\n    grid-template-areas:\n      "header "\n      "sidebar"\n      "main   "\n      "footer ";\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Auto-fill and Auto-fit (Responsive Without Media Queries)\n\n```css\n/* auto-fill: fills row with as many columns as fit */\n.grid {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(280px, 1fr));\n  gap: 1.5rem;\n}\n/* If container is 900px: 3 columns of 300px each */\n/* If container is 600px: 2 columns of 300px each */\n/* If container is 300px: 1 column of 300px */\n\n/* auto-fit: same as auto-fill but collapses empty columns */\n.grid {\n  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr));\n}\n/* If 2 items in a 3-column row, auto-fit stretches them to fill */\n/* auto-fill would leave an empty column */\n\n/* minmax(min, max) — sets minimum and maximum track size */\nminmax(200px, 1fr)    /* Min 200px, grow up to 1fr */\nminmax(100px, 300px)  /* Min 100px, max 300px */\nminmax(auto, 200px)   /* Min = content, max 200px */\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\nGRID LINES (3×3 grid)\n\n      1    2    3    4\n   ┌────┬────┬────┐ ← Row 1\n 1 │ A  │ B  │ C  │\n   ├────┼────┼────┤ ← Row 2\n 2 │ D  │ E  │ F  │\n   ├────┼────┼────┤ ← Row 3\n 3 │ G  │ H  │ I  │\n   └────┴────┴────┘ ← Row 4\n\n   ↑         ↑\n  Col 1    Col 4 (-1)\n\n.A { grid-column: 1 / 3; }  /* Spans A and B columns */\n.A { grid-column: 1 / -1; } /* Spans all columns */\n\n\nNAMED AREAS VISUAL\n\ngrid-template-areas:\n  "header header"\n  "sidebar main  "\n  "footer footer";\n\n┌──────────────────────┐\n│       HEADER         │\n├──────────┬───────────┤\n│          │           │\n│ SIDEBAR  │   MAIN    │\n│          │           │\n├──────────┴───────────┤\n│       FOOTER         │\n└──────────────────────┘\n\n\nauto-fill vs auto-fit (6 items)\n\nauto-fill (3 cols, 1 empty):\n[A][B][C]\n[D][E][F]\n[  ]\n\nauto-fit (3 cols, stretches):\n[A    ][B    ][C    ]\n[D    ][E    ][F    ]\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Complete Layout Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Dashboard Layout\n```css\n.dashboard {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-columns: 240px 1fr;\n  grid-template-rows: 64px 1fr;\n  grid-template-areas:\n    "sidebar topbar"\n    "sidebar content";\n  height: 100vh;\n  overflow: hidden;\n}\n\n.sidebar  { grid-area: sidebar; overflow-y: auto; }\n.topbar   { grid-area: topbar; position: sticky; top: 0; z-index: 10; }\n.content  { grid-area: content; overflow-y: auto; padding: 2rem; }\n\n/* Stats row within content */\n.stats-grid {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr));\n  gap: 1.5rem;\n  margin-bottom: 2rem;\n}\n\n/* Content area grid */\n.content-grid {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr;\n  gap: 1.5rem;\n}\n```\n\n### Example 2 — Magazine Layout\n```css\n.magazine-grid {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-columns: repeat(12, 1fr);\n  grid-template-rows: auto;\n  gap: 1.5rem;\n}\n\n/* Featured article: spans 8 columns, 2 rows */\n.article-featured {\n  grid-column: 1 / 9;\n  grid-row: 1 / 3;\n}\n\n/* Secondary articles: 4 columns each */\n.article-secondary:nth-child(2) { grid-column: 9 / 13; grid-row: 1; }\n.article-secondary:nth-child(3) { grid-column: 9 / 13; grid-row: 2; }\n\n/* Bottom row: 4 columns each */\n.article-small { grid-column: span 4; }\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Auto-Responsive Product Grid\n```css\n.product-grid {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(260px, 1fr));\n  gap: 1.5rem;\n  padding: 1.5rem;\n}\n\n.product-card {\n  background: white;\n  border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;\n  border-radius: 12px;\n  overflow: hidden;\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-rows: 200px auto 1fr auto; /* image | badge | content | cta */\n}\n\n.product-image {\n  grid-row: 1;\n  object-fit: cover;\n  width: 100%;\n  height: 100%;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: When would you use Grid vs Flexbox?**\n> Use Flexbox for one-dimensional layouts (a row of items, a vertical list). Use Grid for two-dimensional layouts where you need control over BOTH rows AND columns simultaneously (page layouts, card grids, dashboards). They can also be nested — Grid for the outer layout, Flex for inner components.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `auto-fill` and `auto-fit`?**\n> Both fill as many columns as fit using `minmax()`. The difference: with `auto-fill`, if there are fewer items than columns, empty columns remain and items don''t stretch. With `auto-fit`, empty columns collapse to zero width and existing items expand to fill the space.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What property enables CSS Grid on a container?\n2. What does `repeat(3, 1fr)` mean?\n3. How do you make an element span the full grid width?\n4. What is the difference between `grid-column: 1 / 3` and `grid-column: span 2`?\n5. What is `minmax()` used for?\n6. What is `auto-fill` vs `auto-fit`?\n7. How do you create named grid areas?\n8. What is the difference between explicit and implicit grid?\n9. How do you set different gaps for rows vs columns?\n10. What does `-1` mean in `grid-column: 1 / -1`?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---------|---------|\n| `display: grid` | Enable Grid |\n| `grid-template-columns` | Define column tracks |\n| `grid-template-areas` | Name regions of the grid |\n| `gap` | Space between tracks |\n| `grid-column: span N` | Item spans N columns |\n| `auto-fill` | Fill row with as many as fit |\n| `minmax()` | Set min and max track size |\n| `fr` | Fraction of remaining space |\n\nCSS Grid eliminates the need for float-based grids, frameworks, and complex positioning hacks. For 2D layout, it is simply the right tool — expressive, powerful, and supported everywhere.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l20601';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Responsive Design & Media Queries — Every Screen, Every User\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nOver 60% of web traffic comes from mobile devices. A website that only looks good on a 1920px desktop is broken for the majority of users. Responsive design means building ONE codebase that adapts beautifully to any screen size.\n\nMedia queries are the CSS mechanism that makes this possible. Combined with flexible units, fluid grids, and modern CSS features like `clamp()` and container queries, you can build UIs that work on a 320px phone screen and a 4K monitor.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Core Concepts\n\n### Media Query Syntax\n\n```css\n/* Basic media query */\n@media (max-width: 768px) {\n  /* Styles for screens 768px wide or smaller */\n  .nav-links { display: none; }\n}\n\n/* Min-width (mobile-first approach — preferred) */\n@media (min-width: 768px) {\n  /* Styles for screens 768px wide or larger */\n  .sidebar { display: block; }\n}\n\n/* Range (modern syntax) */\n@media (768px <= width < 1024px) {\n  /* Tablet styles */\n}\n\n/* Multiple conditions */\n@media (min-width: 768px) and (max-width: 1023px) {\n  /* Tablet only */\n}\n\n/* Orientation */\n@media (orientation: portrait)  { /* Phone portrait */ }\n@media (orientation: landscape) { /* Phone landscape */ }\n\n/* Dark mode preference */\n@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) { body { background: #0f172a; } }\n\n/* Reduced motion (accessibility) */\n@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {\n  *, ::before, ::after {\n    animation-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n    transition-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n  }\n}\n\n/* High contrast */\n@media (prefers-contrast: high) { ... }\n\n/* Print */\n@media print {\n  .nav, .sidebar, .ads { display: none; }\n  body { font-size: 12pt; color: black; }\n}\n```\n\n### Common Breakpoints\n\n```css\n/* Mobile-first breakpoints (Tailwind defaults) */\n:root {\n  --bp-sm:   640px;   /* Small phones and up */\n  --bp-md:   768px;   /* Tablets and up */\n  --bp-lg:   1024px;  /* Small laptops and up */\n  --bp-xl:   1280px;  /* Desktops and up */\n  --bp-2xl:  1536px;  /* Large screens and up */\n}\n\n/* Use min-width queries in ascending order (mobile-first) */\n\n/* Base: mobile (no query) */\n.grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }\n\n/* Tablet+ */\n@media (min-width: 768px) {\n  .grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }\n}\n\n/* Desktop+ */\n@media (min-width: 1024px) {\n  .grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); }\n}\n```\n\n### Container Queries (Modern CSS)\n\n```css\n/* Container queries respond to PARENT size, not viewport */\n.card-container {\n  container-type: inline-size;  /* Enable container queries */\n  container-name: card;\n}\n\n/* Style based on container width */\n@container card (min-width: 400px) {\n  .card { flex-direction: row; }\n  .card-image { width: 200px; }\n}\n\n@container card (max-width: 300px) {\n  .card-title { font-size: 0.875rem; }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. Responsive Patterns\n\n### Pattern 1 — Responsive Navigation\n```css\n/* Mobile: hamburger menu */\n.nav-links {\n  display: none;\n  position: fixed;\n  inset: 0;\n  background: white;\n  flex-direction: column;\n  padding: 5rem 2rem 2rem;\n  z-index: 200;\n}\n\n.nav-links.open { display: flex; }\n\n/* Desktop: horizontal links */\n@media (min-width: 768px) {\n  .nav-links {\n    display: flex;\n    position: static;\n    flex-direction: row;\n    padding: 0;\n    gap: 2rem;\n  }\n  .hamburger { display: none; }\n}\n```\n\n### Pattern 2 — Responsive Image\n```html\n<!-- Always specify dimensions to prevent layout shift -->\n<img\n  src="hero-800.jpg"\n  srcset="\n    hero-400.jpg  400w,\n    hero-800.jpg  800w,\n    hero-1200.jpg 1200w\n  "\n  sizes="\n    (max-width: 640px)  100vw,\n    (max-width: 1024px) 50vw,\n    33vw\n  "\n  width="800"\n  height="450"\n  alt="Hero image"\n  loading="lazy"\n  decoding="async"\n>\n```\n\n```css\n/* Fluid images — always */\nimg {\n  max-width: 100%;\n  height: auto;\n  display: block;\n}\n```\n\n### Pattern 3 — Fluid Typography\n```css\n/* No media queries needed with clamp() */\nhtml { font-size: clamp(14px, 2vw, 18px); }\n\nh1 { font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 4vw, 3rem); }\nh2 { font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 3vw, 2.25rem); }\np  { font-size: clamp(0.875rem, 1.5vw, 1.125rem); }\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is mobile-first design and why is it recommended?**\n> Mobile-first means writing base CSS for mobile and using `min-width` media queries to add styles for larger screens. It''s recommended because: (1) mobile is the majority use case, (2) it forces you to prioritize content over decoration, (3) min-width queries progressively enhance rather than progressively degrade, (4) performance is better (mobile gets minimal CSS, not full CSS overridden).\n\n**Q: What is the difference between media queries and container queries?**\n> Media queries respond to viewport dimensions — they adapt based on screen size. Container queries respond to the size of the element''s parent container — a component can adapt to where it''s placed. Container queries are better for reusable components that might appear in different contexts.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is the difference between `max-width` and `min-width` media queries?\n2. What does `mobile-first` mean in terms of media query approach?\n3. What media feature detects dark mode preference?\n4. What is a container query?\n5. What does `prefers-reduced-motion` control?\n6. How do you make images fluid in CSS?\n7. What is the `srcset` attribute on images?\n8. What are common responsive breakpoints?\n9. How do you hide the desktop navigation on mobile?\n10. What does `@media print` do?\n\n---\n\n## 6. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Technique |\n|---------|----------|\n| Mobile-first | Base mobile CSS + min-width media queries |\n| Fluid grid | `auto-fill` + `minmax()` — no breakpoints |\n| Fluid type | `clamp(min, preferred, max)` |\n| Responsive images | `srcset`, `sizes`, `max-width: 100%` |\n| Container queries | `container-type` + `@container` |\n| Dark mode | `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` |\n| Accessibility | `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` |\n\nResponsive design is not a feature to add at the end — it is a discipline applied from the first line of CSS. Design mobile-first, use flexible units, test on real devices.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l20701';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# CSS Animations & Transitions — Bringing Interfaces to Life\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nAnimation is the difference between a UI that feels alive and one that feels static. But animation done wrong is worse than no animation — janky, distracting, or causing motion sickness. Done right, it communicates state changes, guides attention, and adds polish.\n\nCSS provides two animation systems: transitions (simple state changes) and animations (complex keyframe sequences).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Transitions — Simple State Changes\n\n```css\n/* transition: property duration timing-function delay */\n.btn {\n  background: #3b82f6;\n  transition: background 200ms ease;\n}\n\n.btn:hover {\n  background: #2563eb;\n}\n\n/* Multiple transitions */\n.card {\n  transition:\n    box-shadow 200ms ease,\n    transform 200ms ease,\n    opacity 150ms ease;\n}\n\n.card:hover {\n  box-shadow: 0 20px 40px rgba(0,0,0,0.15);\n  transform: translateY(-4px);\n}\n\n/* transition: all — AVOID in production (performance) */\n/* Only transition properties that actually change */\n\n/* Timing functions */\ntransition-timing-function: ease;            /* Slow start, fast middle, slow end (default) */\ntransition-timing-function: ease-in;         /* Slow start */\ntransition-timing-function: ease-out;        /* Slow end — best for exits */\ntransition-timing-function: ease-in-out;     /* Slow start and end */\ntransition-timing-function: linear;          /* Constant speed */\ntransition-timing-function: cubic-bezier(0.34, 1.56, 0.64, 1); /* Spring */\nsteps(4, end);                               /* Discrete steps (sprite animation) */\n```\n\n## 3. Keyframe Animations\n\n```css\n/* Define animation */\n@keyframes fadeIn {\n  from { opacity: 0; }\n  to   { opacity: 1; }\n}\n\n@keyframes slideInUp {\n  from {\n    opacity: 0;\n    transform: translateY(20px);\n  }\n  to {\n    opacity: 1;\n    transform: translateY(0);\n  }\n}\n\n@keyframes pulse {\n  0%, 100% { transform: scale(1); }\n  50%       { transform: scale(1.05); }\n}\n\n@keyframes spin {\n  from { transform: rotate(0deg); }\n  to   { transform: rotate(360deg); }\n}\n\n@keyframes shimmer {\n  from { background-position: -200% 0; }\n  to   { background-position: 200% 0; }\n}\n\n/* Apply animation */\n.modal {\n  animation:\n    name         duration  timing    delay  iterations  direction  fill-mode;\n/*  slideInUp    300ms     ease-out  0ms    1           normal     both; */\n  animation: slideInUp 300ms ease-out both;\n}\n\n.loading-spinner {\n  animation: spin 1s linear infinite;\n}\n\n.notification-badge {\n  animation: pulse 2s ease-in-out infinite;\n}\n```\n\n## 4. Performance-Optimized Animations\n\n```css\n/* GPU-accelerated properties (smooth, no reflow) */\ntransform: translate(), scale(), rotate(), skew();\nopacity: 0 to 1;\n\n/* CPU-heavy properties (causes layout reflow — AVOID) */\nwidth, height, margin, padding, top, left, font-size\n\n/* WRONG: animating width */\n.panel {\n  width: 0;\n  transition: width 300ms ease;\n}\n.panel.open { width: 300px; }  /* Causes layout shift for ALL elements */\n\n/* BETTER: animate transform */\n.panel {\n  transform: scaleX(0);\n  transform-origin: left;\n  transition: transform 300ms ease;\n}\n.panel.open { transform: scaleX(1); }\n\n/* will-change — hint to browser to optimize */\n.animating {\n  will-change: transform, opacity;\n  /* Add before animation, remove after */\n}\n```\n\n## 5. Practical Animation Patterns\n\n### Loading Skeleton\n```css\n.skeleton {\n  background: linear-gradient(\n    90deg,\n    #f1f5f9 25%,\n    #e2e8f0 50%,\n    #f1f5f9 75%\n  );\n  background-size: 200% 100%;\n  animation: shimmer 1.5s infinite;\n  border-radius: 8px;\n}\n```\n\n### Accordion Open/Close\n```css\n.accordion-content {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-rows: 0fr;\n  transition: grid-template-rows 300ms ease;\n}\n\n.accordion-content.open {\n  grid-template-rows: 1fr;\n}\n\n.accordion-inner {\n  overflow: hidden;\n}\n```\n\n### Staggered List Animation\n```css\n@keyframes fadeInUp {\n  from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(16px); }\n  to   { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }\n}\n\n.list-item {\n  animation: fadeInUp 400ms ease both;\n}\n\n.list-item:nth-child(1) { animation-delay: 0ms; }\n.list-item:nth-child(2) { animation-delay: 75ms; }\n.list-item:nth-child(3) { animation-delay: 150ms; }\n.list-item:nth-child(4) { animation-delay: 225ms; }\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Accessibility — Respecting User Preferences\n\n```css\n/* ALWAYS respect reduced-motion preferences */\n@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {\n  *, ::before, ::after {\n    animation-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n    animation-iteration-count: 1 !important;\n    transition-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n    scroll-behavior: auto !important;\n  }\n}\n\n/* Alternative: opt-in pattern */\n@media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference) {\n  .hero { animation: fadeIn 600ms ease both; }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What CSS properties should you animate for the best performance?**\n> Only `transform` and `opacity`. These are GPU-accelerated and do not cause layout reflow or paint. Animating `width`, `height`, `margin`, `top`, `left`, or other layout properties causes the browser to recalculate layout for the entire document, which is expensive (causes jank).\n\n**Q: What is the difference between CSS transitions and animations?**\n> Transitions: simple state changes triggered by events (hover, focus, class toggle). They only have start and end states. Animations: complex sequences with `@keyframes` defining intermediate states. They can loop, reverse, and run automatically without user interaction.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What CSS properties animate without causing layout reflow?\n2. What does `animation-fill-mode: both` do?\n3. What timing function should you use for elements exiting the screen?\n4. How do you make an animation loop infinitely?\n5. What does `will-change: transform` do?\n6. What media feature should you always check for accessible animations?\n7. What is the difference between `transition` and `animation`?\n8. How do you delay an animation by 200ms?\n9. What does `@keyframes` define?\n10. How do you stop an animation that is playing?\n\n---\n\n## 9. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| `transition` | State changes: from → to on event |\n| `@keyframes` | Define multi-step animation sequences |\n| `animation` | Apply keyframe animation to element |\n| GPU properties | `transform` and `opacity` only |\n| `ease-out` | Best for elements appearing on screen |\n| `prefers-reduced-motion` | ALWAYS respect — accessibility |\n| `will-change` | Performance hint — use sparingly |\n\nAnimation is communication. Every motion in your UI should have a purpose — confirm an action, show a state change, guide attention. Keep animations short (150-400ms), respect user preferences, and always animate GPU-accelerated properties.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l20801';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# CSS Variables & Architecture — Scalable Stylesheets\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nAs CSS codebases grow, they become impossible to maintain without a system. CSS Custom Properties (variables) and CSS architecture methodologies (BEM, utility-first) are what separate maintainable professional CSS from the "one change breaks everything" nightmare.\n\nCSS Custom Properties are not just for colors — they enable dynamic theming, component variants, responsive systems, and dark mode with minimal code.\n\n---\n\n## 2. CSS Custom Properties (Variables)\n\n```css\n/* Define in :root for global scope */\n:root {\n  /* Design tokens */\n  --color-brand:     #3b82f6;\n  --color-brand-dark: #2563eb;\n  --color-bg:        #ffffff;\n  --color-text:      #0f172a;\n  --color-border:    #e2e8f0;\n\n  --space-1: 0.25rem;\n  --space-2: 0.5rem;\n  --space-4: 1rem;\n  --space-6: 1.5rem;\n  --space-8: 2rem;\n\n  --radius-sm: 4px;\n  --radius-md: 8px;\n  --radius-lg: 12px;\n  --radius-full: 9999px;\n\n  --shadow-sm:  0 1px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);\n  --shadow-md:  0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);\n  --shadow-lg:  0 10px 15px -3px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);\n}\n\n/* Use */\n.btn {\n  background: var(--color-brand);\n  padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4);\n  border-radius: var(--radius-md);\n  box-shadow: var(--shadow-sm);\n}\n\n/* With fallback */\n.btn { color: var(--color-text, #000); }\n\n/* Dynamic dark mode */\n@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {\n  :root {\n    --color-bg: #0f172a;\n    --color-text: #f1f5f9;\n    --color-border: #334155;\n  }\n}\n/* All components using these variables automatically update! */\n\n/* Scoped variables */\n.card { --padding: 1.5rem; }\n.card-compact { --padding: 0.75rem; }\n/* card components use var(--padding) */\n\n/* JS can read/write CSS variables */\ndocument.documentElement.style.setProperty(''--color-brand'', ''#10b981'');\ndocument.documentElement.style.getPropertyValue(''--color-brand'');\n```\n\n## 3. CSS Architecture — BEM Methodology\n\n```css\n/* BEM: Block__Element--Modifier */\n\n/* Block: standalone component */\n.card { ... }\n\n/* Element: part of the block */\n.card__image  { ... }\n.card__body   { ... }\n.card__title  { ... }\n.card__footer { ... }\n\n/* Modifier: variant or state */\n.card--featured  { border: 2px solid gold; }\n.card--compact   { padding: 0.75rem; }\n.card--loading   { opacity: 0.6; }\n\n/* Combined */\n.card__title--truncated {\n  overflow: hidden;\n  text-overflow: ellipsis;\n  white-space: nowrap;\n}\n```\n\n## 4. CSS Layers (Modern Architecture)\n\n```css\n/* @layer controls specificity order — last layer wins */\n@layer reset, base, components, utilities;\n\n@layer reset {\n  *, *::before, *::after { box-sizing: border-box; }\n  * { margin: 0; }\n}\n\n@layer base {\n  body { font-family: var(--font-sans); }\n  h1   { font-size: 2.25rem; }\n}\n\n@layer components {\n  .btn { /* component styles */ }\n  .card { /* component styles */ }\n}\n\n@layer utilities {\n  .hidden { display: none; }\n  .sr-only { /* screen reader only */ }\n}\n\n/* Utilities always win over components, regardless of specificity */\n```\n\n## 5. Design Token System Example\n\n```css\n:root {\n  /* Primitive tokens */\n  --blue-50: #eff6ff;\n  --blue-500: #3b82f6;\n  --blue-700: #1d4ed8;\n\n  /* Semantic tokens (reference primitives) */\n  --color-action:        var(--blue-500);\n  --color-action-hover:  var(--blue-700);\n  --color-action-subtle: var(--blue-50);\n\n  /* Component tokens (reference semantics) */\n  --btn-bg:          var(--color-action);\n  --btn-bg-hover:    var(--color-action-hover);\n  --btn-text:        white;\n  --btn-radius:      var(--radius-md);\n}\n\n.btn-primary {\n  background: var(--btn-bg);\n  color: var(--btn-text);\n  border-radius: var(--btn-radius);\n}\n\n.btn-primary:hover {\n  background: var(--btn-bg-hover);\n}\n\n/* Theme swap: only change semantic tokens */\n.theme-green {\n  --color-action:       #10b981;\n  --color-action-hover: #059669;\n  --color-action-subtle: #ecfdf5;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between CSS custom properties and Sass variables?**\n> Sass variables are preprocessed — they become static values in the final CSS and cannot be changed at runtime. CSS custom properties exist in the browser — they can be changed via JavaScript, they cascade and inherit like regular CSS properties, they respond to media queries, and they can be overridden per-selector for component theming.\n\n**Q: How do CSS Custom Properties enable dark mode?**\n> Define all colors as custom properties in `:root`. Add a `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` block that overrides only the custom property values. All components using `var(--color-text)`, `var(--color-bg)`, etc. automatically update because the variables change — no need to update component styles at all.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. How do you define a CSS custom property?\n2. What is the syntax for using a custom property with a fallback?\n3. What is the scope of `:root` variables?\n4. How do custom properties differ from Sass variables?\n5. What is BEM and what does it stand for?\n6. What are CSS `@layer`s used for?\n7. How do you read/write CSS variables from JavaScript?\n8. What are design tokens?\n9. Can custom properties be animated?\n10. What does `@layer utilities` winning over `@layer components` mean?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| `--variable` | Define custom property |\n| `var(--name)` | Use custom property |\n| `var(--name, fallback)` | Use with fallback value |\n| `:root` | Global scope for tokens |\n| BEM | Block__Element--Modifier naming |\n| `@layer` | Control specificity order |\n| Design tokens | Semantic names for values |\n\nCSS architecture is what keeps large codebases maintainable. Variables + consistent naming + layers = a CSS codebase that can be maintained by a team without specificity battles.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l20901';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Tailwind CSS Fundamentals — Utility-First in Practice\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nTailwind CSS is a utility-first CSS framework that provides thousands of small, single-purpose classes. Instead of writing `.card { display: flex; gap: 1rem; }` in a CSS file, you write `<div class="flex gap-4">` directly in HTML.\n\nThis approach sounds unusual until you try it — then most developers never go back. Tailwind is used by companies like GitHub, Shopify, Vercel, and Supabase.\n\n> **R-Learn uses Tailwind CSS** throughout this platform''s UI. Every card, button, and layout you see is built with Tailwind.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Core Concepts\n\n### Utility Classes Map to CSS Properties\n\n```html\n<!-- Traditional CSS approach -->\n<div class="card">...</div>\n<!-- .card { display: flex; gap: 1rem; padding: 1.5rem; background: white; border-radius: 12px; } -->\n\n<!-- Tailwind utility approach -->\n<div class="flex gap-4 p-6 bg-white rounded-xl">...</div>\n```\n\n### Common Utility Classes\n\n```html\n<!-- Layout -->\n<div class="flex flex-col gap-4">       <!-- Flexbox column -->\n<div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-6">   <!-- 3-col grid -->\n<div class="hidden md:block">          <!-- Responsive -->\n\n<!-- Spacing -->\n<div class="p-4">                      <!-- padding: 1rem -->\n<div class="px-6 py-3">               <!-- x:1.5rem, y:0.75rem -->\n<div class="m-auto">                  <!-- margin: auto -->\n<div class="mt-8 mb-4">              <!-- margin-top: 2rem; bottom: 1rem -->\n<div class="space-y-4">             <!-- children: margin-top: 1rem -->\n\n<!-- Sizing -->\n<div class="w-full">                  <!-- width: 100% -->\n<div class="w-64">                    <!-- width: 16rem -->\n<div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto">      <!-- max-width: 42rem; centered -->\n<div class="h-screen">              <!-- height: 100vh -->\n\n<!-- Typography -->\n<h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">   <!-- size, weight, color -->\n<p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed"> <!-- small muted text -->\n<span class="font-medium text-blue-600">         <!-- medium weight, blue -->\n\n<!-- Colors -->\n<div class="bg-blue-500 text-white">             <!-- background + text -->\n<div class="bg-gray-100 text-gray-800">          <!-- muted card -->\n<button class="bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700">   <!-- hover state -->\n\n<!-- Borders & Shadows -->\n<div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg shadow-md">\n<div class="border-2 border-blue-500 rounded-full">\n\n<!-- Positioning -->\n<div class="relative">                           <!-- position: relative -->\n<div class="absolute inset-0">                  <!-- all sides 0 -->\n<div class="sticky top-0 z-50">               <!-- sticky + z-index -->\n\n<!-- Display -->\n<div class="hidden">                             <!-- display: none -->\n<div class="invisible">                         <!-- visibility: hidden -->\n<span class="inline-flex items-center gap-2">   <!-- inline-flex -->\n```\n\n### Tailwind Spacing Scale\n\n```\nEach unit = 4px (0.25rem)\n1 = 4px    2 = 8px    3 = 12px   4 = 16px\n5 = 20px   6 = 24px   8 = 32px   10 = 40px\n12 = 48px  16 = 64px  20 = 80px  24 = 96px\n```\n\n### Responsive Prefixes\n\n```html\n<!-- sm: md: lg: xl: 2xl: — mobile-first breakpoints -->\n<div class="w-full md:w-1/2 lg:w-1/3">\n  <!-- Full on mobile, half on tablet, third on desktop -->\n</div>\n\n<nav class="hidden md:flex gap-8">\n  <!-- Hidden on mobile, flex on tablet+ -->\n</nav>\n\n<div class="text-base lg:text-xl">\n  <!-- Smaller text on mobile, larger on desktop -->\n</div>\n```\n\n### State Variants\n\n```html\n<!-- hover: focus: active: disabled: -->\n<button class="bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700 active:bg-blue-800\n               focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-blue-500\n               disabled:opacity-50 disabled:cursor-not-allowed\">\n  Submit\n</button>\n\n<!-- group: — parent hover affects children -->\n<div class="group cursor-pointer\">\n  <h3 class="text-gray-900 group-hover:text-blue-600\">Title</h3>\n  <p class="text-gray-500 group-hover:text-gray-700">Description</p>\n</div>\n\n<!-- peer: — sibling state -->\n<input type="checkbox" id="toggle" class="peer hidden\">\n<label for="toggle" class="...">Show more</label>\n<div class="hidden peer-checked:block\">Hidden content</div>\n\n<!-- dark: — dark mode -->\n<div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100\">\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. Building Components\n\n### Button Component\n```html\n<!-- Primary button -->\n<button\n  type="button"\n  class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700\n         active:bg-blue-800 text-white text-sm font-medium rounded-lg\n         transition-colors duration-150 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2\n         focus:ring-blue-500 focus:ring-offset-2 disabled:opacity-50\n         disabled:cursor-not-allowed"\n>\n  <svg class="w-4 h-4" ...></svg>\n  Enroll Now\n</button>\n\n<!-- Ghost button -->\n<button\n  class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 border border-gray-300\n         hover:border-gray-400 text-gray-700 text-sm font-medium rounded-lg\n         transition-colors duration-150 hover:bg-gray-50"\n>\n  View Details\n</button>\n```\n\n### Course Card\n```html\n<article class="bg-white border border-gray-200 rounded-xl overflow-hidden\n                hover:shadow-lg transition-shadow duration-200 group">\n  <div class="aspect-video overflow-hidden">\n    <img\n      src="course-thumb.jpg"\n      alt="Course thumbnail"\n      class="w-full h-full object-cover group-hover:scale-105 transition-transform duration-300"\n    >\n  </div>\n\n  <div class="p-5">\n    <span class="inline-block px-2.5 py-0.5 bg-blue-50 text-blue-700\n                 text-xs font-medium rounded-full mb-3">\n      Frontend\n    </span>\n\n    <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2 line-clamp-2\n               group-hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors">\n      <a href="/courses/html5" class="stretched-link">HTML5 Fundamentals</a>\n    </h3>\n\n    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4 line-clamp-2">\n      Learn HTML5 from scratch with 12 modules and hands-on projects.\n    </p>\n\n    <div class="flex items-center justify-between text-xs text-gray-500">\n      <span>12 modules</span>\n      <span>10 hours</span>\n      <span class="flex items-center gap-1">\n        <span class="text-yellow-500">★</span> 4.8\n      </span>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</article>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is utility-first CSS and how does Tailwind implement it?**\n> Utility-first means styling with single-purpose classes instead of component-level CSS. Tailwind provides classes like `flex`, `p-4`, `text-blue-600` that map directly to CSS declarations. Instead of creating custom component classes, you compose multiple utility classes directly in HTML. The production build uses PurgeCSS to include only classes actually used.\n\n**Q: What are the advantages and disadvantages of Tailwind?**\n> Advantages: No context switching between HTML and CSS, no naming problems, responsive/state variants built in, consistent design system, tiny production bundle. Disadvantages: HTML can get verbose, harder to extract reusable patterns, requires learning the utility names, not ideal for complex CSS that utilities can''t express cleanly.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does `p-4` map to in CSS?\n2. How do you make an element visible only on desktop in Tailwind?\n3. What is the `group` class used for?\n4. How do you add a hover effect in Tailwind?\n5. What does `truncate` do in Tailwind?\n6. How do you add dark mode styles?\n7. What is `sr-only` used for?\n8. How do you center a container with Tailwind?\n9. What does `line-clamp-2` do?\n10. How do you add a focus ring for accessibility?\n\n---\n\n## 6. Lesson Summary\n\n| Pattern | Tailwind Classes |\n|---------|------------------|\n| Flex row centered | `flex items-center gap-4` |\n| Responsive grid | `grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3` |\n| Button primary | `px-4 py-2 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-lg` |\n| Card | `bg-white border border-gray-200 rounded-xl p-6` |\n| Hover effect | `hover:bg-blue-700 transition-colors` |\n| Dark mode | `bg-white dark:bg-gray-900` |\n| Responsive show/hide | `hidden md:block` |\n\nTailwind is the fastest way to build consistent, responsive UIs. Once you internalize the utility vocabulary, you''ll never want to write separate CSS files again.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l21001';
